=== Tuples and Lists

Two of the most common container types are tuples and lists. Tuples have a fixed
size and may contain elements with different types. Lists have variable size but
contain elements all of the same type.

Tuples and lists both are translated into JSON as arrays. So from the JSON alone
it is impossible to tell if a value such as `[1,2,3]` is a list of integers or a
tuple of three integers.

==== Tuples

Tuples may be used to store a fixed number of terms of different type.

[source, morloc]
----
x :: (Int, Bool, Real)
x = (1, True, 6.45)
----

Tuple types and tuple values are both represented as comma-delimited values
within parentheses. The parenthesized type representation is syntactic sugar for
a fixed-size tuple type such as `Tuple3` or `Tuple8`; the parser generates the
appropriate `TupleN` form from the number of fields, so there is no fixed upper
bound on tuple arity. Generally, if you have more than a few members in a
tuple, it is better to define a record type with named values.

==== Lists

Lists are homogeneous, variable-length sequences of values. The base list type
is `List a`, which can be written as `[a]`:

[source, morloc]
----
x :: [Int]
x = [1, 2, 3]

ys :: List Real
ys = [1.0, 2.0, 3.0]
----

The default `List` type maps to each language's natural ordered container
(`list` in Python, `std::vector` in {cpp}, list/vector in R). For
alternatives such as `Deque`, `Vector`, and `Array`, see the
<<Type hierarchies>> chapter.

==== List operations are sourced functions

Lists do not yet have dedicated accessor syntax. Operations on lists are
ordinary functions and typeclass methods drawn from the `root` standard
library; importing `root-py` (or `root-cpp`/`root-r`) brings them into scope
along with their language-specific implementations.

The operations group by typeclass:

[cols="1,2,3", options="header"]
|===
| Typeclass | Methods | Notes

| `Functor`
| `map`
| `map :: (a -> b) -> [a] -> [b]`

| `Foldable`
| `fold`, `fold1`, `safeFold1`, `length`, `sum`, `any`, `all`, `elem`, `concat`, `concatMap`
| `length` requires `Foldable`; works on `[a]` but *not* on `Str`

| `Indexed`
| `at`, `slice`
| `at 0 [1,2,3] == 1`; `slice i j xs` returns `xs[i..j-1]` (half-open)

| `Stack`
| `cons`, `uncons`
| Prepend / split-from-front

| `Queue`
| `snoc`, `unsnoc`
| Append / split-from-back

| `Semigroup`, `Monoid`
| `<>`, `mempty`
| `[1,2] <> [3,4] == [1,2,3,4]`; `mempty :: [a]` is `[]`

| Free-standing list functions
| `reverse`, `sort`, `sortBy`, `groupSort`, `filter`, `takeWhile`, `dropWhile`, `partition`, `scanl`, `iterate`, `replicate`, `intersperse`, `intercalate`, `enumerate`, `groupBy`, `find`, `unique`, `zip`, `zipWith`, `unzip`, `range`, `rangeStep`, `toDeque`, `toArray`
| Defined in `root` for `List`; see `root/main.loc`
|===

==== Ranges and slices share half-open bounds

`range`, `rangeStep`, and `slice` all use Python-style half-open upper
bounds, so a length-`N` walk reads the same in every form:

[cols="1,2", options="header"]
|===
| Expression | Result

| `range 0 5`
| `[0, 1, 2, 3, 4]` (5 elements)

| `rangeStep 0 10 2`
| `[0, 2, 4, 6, 8]` (5 elements)

| `slice 0 5 xs`
| First five elements of `xs`
|===

The upper index is never included; to enumerate `1..N` write `range 1 (N+1)`.

==== Concatenation and empty lists

Lists support concatenation through the `Semigroup` operator `<>` and the
`Monoid` identity `mempty`:

[source, morloc]
----
xs :: [Int]
xs = [1, 2] <> [3, 4]   -- [1, 2, 3, 4]

empty :: [Int]
empty = mempty           -- []
----

The same `<>` operator concatenates strings, deques, and arrays where those
have `Semigroup` instances.

==== Alternative sequence types

`List` is the default. The standard library also defines `Deque` (O(1)
front-and-back access), `Vector` (O(1) random access, growable at the end),
and `Array` (fixed-size random-access). These share the typeclass surface
with `List` to varying degrees; see the <<Type hierarchies>> chapter and the
`root` module documentation for the exact instance coverage.
